    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target value="3380">
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The assumption is to train 70% males of the total trained, 2020 will estimate 1 training per month of 30 participants, 2021 - 2025 an estimate of 3 of 30 participants per training per month. Numbers do not include in-service training (uvailable later)</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual value="140">
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The number of male police officers attending training has increasd and been balanced because those that attend training are nominated which help to maintain a balance. General CSO/NGO facilitators reported improvements in knowledge, attitudes and proactises by police officers towards SW, PWUD and LGBTIQ when they seek help and services from police officers. It was reported by SW that some male police officers had gone an extra mile to help SW if a client had declined to pay for SW services. This is was a very usual act by a police officer. A good number of police officers also showed interest in joining Champions/Ambassadors groups in all the provinces. This is a good way ot starting peer to peer actions among police officers. It is sad that the programme lost the police officer due to COVID19 complications from Gauteng Provincial officer spear heading formation of Champions/Ambassadors group in Gauteng.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target value="5">
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The assumption is to identify and train 1 transgender police officer per year. Numbers do not include in-service training (available later)</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual value="1">
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">There was one police officers reporting to be gender non-conforming. Although the ambassadors/champions groups does have transgernder it is hard to get training representatives when nominations are done. Champions/Ambassadors will be utilised to nominate transgender police officers to attend the DDP training in the provinces.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target value="1450">
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The assumption is to train 30% females. Numbers do not include in-service training (available later)</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual value="189">
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Training took place in Nelspriut (Mpumalanga), Bloemfontein) (Free State, Potchefstroum (Nortn West), Bisho (Eastern Cape), Hluhluwe (KZN), eThekweni (KZN), Newcatsle (KZN), Ugu (KZN), Ugungundlovu (KZN). The training focused on some rural areas of KZN, Mpumalanga, Free State, Eastern Cape and North West provinces. All the training was conducted from September to December 2020. Generally sex workers who shared their stories at some of the training reported improvement in knowledge, attitudes and practices by law enforcement officers. This maybe linked to the training and other interventions at the level of  Deputy Police Minister who has shown committment to improvement on human rights for SW and KPs in general.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
